        -:   38:
        -:   39:// Evaluators have to be specialized with respect to various criteria such as:
        -:   40://  - storage/structure/shape
        -:   41://  - scalar type
        -:   42://  - etc.
        -:   43:// Therefore, we need specialization of evaluator providing additional template arguments for each kind of evaluators.
        -:   44:// We currently distinguish the following kind of evaluators:
        -:   45:// - unary_evaluator    for expressions taking only one arguments (CwiseUnaryOp, CwiseUnaryView, Transpose, MatrixWrapper, ArrayWrapper, Reverse, Replicate)
        -:   46:// - binary_evaluator   for expression taking two arguments (CwiseBinaryOp)
        -:   47:// - ternary_evaluator   for expression taking three arguments (CwiseTernaryOp)
        -:   48:// - product_evaluator  for linear algebra products (Product); special case of binary_evaluator because it requires additional tags for dispatching.
        -:   49:// - mapbase_evaluator  for Map, Block, Ref
        -:   50:// - block_evaluator    for Block (special dispatching to a mapbase_evaluator or unary_evaluator)
        -:   51:
        -:   52:template< typename T,
        -:   53:          typename Arg1Kind   = typename evaluator_traits<typename T::Arg1>::Kind,
        -:   54:          typename Arg2Kind   = typename evaluator_traits<typename T::Arg2>::Kind,
        -:   55:          typename Arg3Kind   = typename evaluator_traits<typename T::Arg3>::Kind,
        -:   56:          typename Arg1Scalar = typename traits<typename T::Arg1>::Scalar,
        -:   57:          typename Arg2Scalar = typename traits<typename T::Arg2>::Scalar,
        -:   58:          typename Arg3Scalar = typename traits<typename T::Arg3>::Scalar> struct ternary_evaluator;
